{{DISPLAYTITLE:<span style="color: white; text-shadow: 1px 3px 0 #0000FF, 1px 9px 5px #aba8a8"><span style = "color:#ADD8E6"><span style="font-family:Jost;">'''Level 369: Clear Forecast'''</span></span></span>}}
{{Background|file=NeighbourhoodStopSign.jpg}}
<div style="font-family:Jost; background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.25); border:3px solid #FFFFFF; box-shadow: 0px 0px 7px #FFFFFF; padding:5px 10px; margin:1em">
{{Class Variable|security=Varying Stability|entity=Lack of Harmful Entities}}
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="6">《 Physical Description 》</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="5">《 The Station 》</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
{{Blurimage|file=Thestation1lessblurry.png|caption=One of many hallways within the Station.}}
'''The Station''' is the first area one encounters upon entering '''Level 369'''. It encompasses a large non-Euclidean warehouse housing interconnected hallways and large rooms. The hallways possess traits such as carpeted or tiled flooring and white drywall. Some hallways retain a ceiling of fiberglass tiles and fluorescent lighting. However, the ceiling is not always prevalent, and one is often able to spot exposed crisscrossing metal and pipes all painted in a black hue. In these cases, lighting is provided via mounted wall lights and individual lamps. Additional objects such as chairs, small tables, TVs, and empty vending machines can also be encountered within the hallways. Rarely, bottles of [[Object 1|Almond Water]] can be found on tables and chairs.

Doors are a common sight within the '''Station's''' hallways and often sport bright red EXIT signs over them. Regardless, the doors always lead to one of a few different copy-and-paste room types. Most commonly, one can find large recording studios with a multitude of camera equipment, a soundstage, and a large projector in the center. Sound is amplified in certain areas and muted within others, assumed to be a result of an anomalous soundproofing effect. Realistically, one is able to tamper with these components, though doing so will anger the '''News Crew'''. Aside from the studios, break rooms and lobby areas can be located within the '''Station''', the latter being the rarest type and the only method of entry and egress to and from the '''Station'''.  Altogether, the '''Station''' has a total surface area of 14,000 square miles.

The entirety of the '''Station''' has a large amount of instability. Hallways are capable of changing shape, rooms often move positions, and objects can disappear once out of sight. Additionally, the '''Station's''' lighting is not always constant, resulting in many dark and dimly illuminated areas. These sections are typically more mazelike than the rest of the '''Station''', and all non-Euclidean attributes are amplified to a point where one can be trapped in their own box of drywall. Rooms are more stable than the hallways and are only shifted around the '''Station's''' layout. Besides these properties, the '''Station''' retains no other hazards, though it is still recommended to locate an exit swiftly due to the '''Station's''' almost complete lack of resources.

Exiting the '''Station''' involves locating a lobby, as aforementioned. The lobbies are simple rooms with a small reception desk, a set of 10 chairs arranged into two rows, and a window on the outside wall. A set of double doors sits next to the window and allows one to leave '''The Station'''.
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="5">《 The Outside 》</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
{{Blurimage|file=NeighbourhoodStopSign.jpg|caption=One of the many neighborhoods within '''Level 369'''.}}
Beyond the confines of the '''Station''' lies the remainder of '''Level 369''', known as the '''Outside'''. Upon exiting the '''Station''', one will be met by a small parking lot that surrounds the building, filled with a large number of cars. From the outside, the '''Station''' takes on an appearance similar to a regular-sized warehouse. Since exiting the '''Station''' only puts one on a singular side of the building, one is consistently treated to a similar initial view. Examining the parking lot reveals many inconsistencies and abnormalities, such as wooden tires, cars made out of materials such as bubble wrap, cardboard, and liquid mercury, and unrealistically shaped objects. Utilizing the double doors allows one reentry into the '''Station''', though this is unrecommended unless one specifically wishes to exploit an exit within it.

Traveling a few blocks in any direction away from the '''Station''' brings one to a set of towns. These towns are centered around their own main squares and are arranged in a grid pattern spanning for approximately 0.5 miles. The towns contain typical buildings important to any municipal government/services, mainly a town hall, bank, and courthouse. All buildings have either traditional or modern architecture, with no in-between or mix, and the interior showcases a similar desolate nature. A circular ring road encircles the '''Station''' and connects each town at its corners, with perpendicular roads radiating from it that traverse '''Level 369'''. These roads share similar features to US standard road markings, with double yellow lines running down the center and a bike lane along the shoulders.

For 50 miles outside the ring road circle, '''Level 369''' is purely composed of neighborhoods resembling American-style suburbia, with large single-family homes, perfectly manicured lawns, and wide cul-de-sac streets. Unlike within the towns, the houses appear to be constructed within the 2010s and retain a slight extradimensional quality within their interiors, as the layout is typically different from their exterior appearances. Houses always retain two stories and have a singular living room/kitchen combination; however, the placement of other rooms is widely varied. In some cases, houses may lack bedrooms or bathrooms entirely.
{{Blurimage|file=Theoutside1.png|caption=The rural exterior}}
The remainder of '''Level 369''' beyond the 50-mile mark is an infinite expanse of rural rolling hills and fields. Within these areas, density is limited to only singular farms, small houses, and rest stops. It is common to see crops such as corn and wheat grow within isolated fields, which are edible. Structures are able to be entered here similarly to the rest of '''Level 369''', though each structure's interior contains the same layout. Rest stops have an oblong or L-shaped placement, while houses have a more uniform line shape. Temperature also acclimates according to the outside temperature. Traversing far enough results in the hills increasing in height until reaching a similar point to Mount Everest (approximately 30,000 feet or 9144 meters) before quickly descending into an endless, flat plain. Within these flat areas, buildings are larger, and other structures such as barns will become viewable.

Overall, the Outside always retains a 26-hour day/night cycle, similar to the [[The Frontrooms|Frontrooms]], with 16 hours of daylight and 10 hours of night. Temperatures typically reach a high of 77 degrees Fahrenheit (25 degrees Celsius) during the day and 41 degrees Fahrenheit (5 degrees Celsius) during the night. This metric is subject to change during certain days and '''Weather Events'''. A light source has yet to be identified, in both daytime and nighttime, leading to many believing that '''Level 369''' produces its own light, or that the light is entirely controlled by the '''Station'''. Additionally, the '''Outside''' is dotted with TVs in various formats, ranging from the 1970s to the 2020s era. The TVs can be in a large number of places, such as inside and along the walls of buildings, on lampposts, and even tucked in more unorthodox places, including within trees and replacing windows.
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="6">《 Entities 》</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="5">《 The News Crew 》</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
'''The News Crew''' are the primary entities of '''Level 369''' and can be spotted within the '''Station''' and the towns in the '''Outside'''. '''The News Crew''' appear similar to humans, though they sport a large 80's-era TV on their heads and are always dressed in the same attire of a black T-shirt, jeans, and running shoes. Instances of the '''News Crew''' primarily communicate with each other through a series of beeps and bops, assumed to be a form of Morse code that is known to only themselves. However, instances are capable of communication with wanderers through their TV head, with a limited number of characters and words to express differing emotions.

'''The News Crew''' are mostly passive entities and usually stay out of the way of wanderers, though they will sometimes engage in small talk when one crosses paths. However, once provoked, they will begin to release a series of sound waves measured at 70,000 hertz, a level in which the human ear is vastly sensitive towards. These sound waves trigger a series of headaches, dizziness, and fatigue slowly increasing with time. Eventually, one will pass out and noclip through the floor before waking in a random space within the '''Station'''. Continually provoking a '''News Crew''' instance will result in increasing hostility, eventually leading to one being forced out of '''Level 369''' completely. If one is forced out, all entrances will send one to [[Level 370]] instead.

It is confirmed that instances are unable to form emotional bonds with wanderers. Despite this facet, many groups within '''Level 369''' made numerous attempts to "domesticate" the '''News Crew''', which only resulted in many individuals perishing within the '''Station''' or being forced out of the level.
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="5">《 The Weatherman 》</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
'''The Weatherman''' is a mysterious entity that is rumored to control '''Level 369''' from the sidelines. Unlike the '''News Crew''', the '''Weatherman''' has never been spotted in person, instead appearing on TVs. The '''Weatherman''' appears as a Caucasian male dressed in a formal suit and tie, though one is unable to recall further details about his appearance, seemingly erased from one's mind once each TV is turned off. Attempts to write down his exact traits have failed and recording devices buffer or shut off entirely. As a result, his true appearance is ambiguous.

During the "morning" of '''Level 369's''' day/night cycle, the '''Weatherman''' appears on all TVs and describes the expected forecast for the day's weather, alongside the number of clouds within the sky and abnormal weather events that are set to take place. The '''Weatherman's''' forecasts are always accurate, down to the exact time of events. As a result, it is imperative to watch the '''Weatherman's''' broadcasts, due to them providing crucial information.

'''The News Crew''' is very loyal towards the '''Weatherman''' and will waste no time in praising the '''Weatherman''' if one asks about him. However, if one pushes deeper questions about the '''Weatherman''', such as his location, detailed appearance, or how he does his forecasts, instances will change subject. Further pressure may result in '''News Crew''' instances entering their hostile state. Insulting the '''Weatherman''' will immediately force one out of '''Level 369''' with no additional chances.

Currently, it is assumed that the '''Weatherman''' controls '''Level 369's''' weather and has authority over the '''News Crew''', explaining the accuracy of his broadcasts and the '''News Crew's''' unwavering loyalty towards him. Many other theories were crafted as '''Level 369''' became more inhabited, with many believing that the '''Weatherman''' is not a physical being and is instead an apparition operating from the TVs. If he is truly a physical being, many presume that he is located in a hidden room within the '''Station''' only accessible to him and the '''News Crew'''.
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="6">《 Weather Events 》</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
Although one's first glance may suggest the opposite, the weather patterns in '''Level 369''' are unpredictable and are capable of changing through so-called '''Weather Events'''. '''Weather Events''' are typically deadly and often anomalous natural disasters that affect the whole of '''Level 369'''. '''Weather Events''' usually begin during the "afternoon" phase of each day and progress until nighttime, where any damage and remnants are repaired upon the next day. Strangely, buildings remain unscathed throughout the raging weather via unknown means, making them the only optimal shelters.

Proceeding a '''Weather Event''', the '''Weatherman''' will mention a "newly discovered geographical anomaly" during the morning broadcast, while never explaining in deeper detail. One minute before a '''Weather Event''' takes place, the '''Weatherman''' will make an emergency broadcast, where he will announce that a major weather anomaly is set to hit before further explaining the storm, including names and properties. The broadcast ends by telling individuals to seek immediate shelter, before a timer appears on each TV counting down from 60 seconds. Once the timer concludes, the storm will quickly sweep through the level, dragging any unfortunate individuals into its grasp.

These events only further add on to the '''Weatherman''' potentially controlling '''Level 369's''' weather or having a sort of know-how in the level's patterns. Nevertheless, it is still unconfirmed. '''Weather Events''' occur once every 2 weeks to 3 months.
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="5">《 Documented Weather Events 》</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<tabber>
|-|Hurricane Typhoid (1991)=
<span style="color:black; text-shadow: 0 0 4px white, 0 0 6px white, 0 0 8px white, 0 0 10px white"></span>
<div style="background-color:white;color:red;margin:auto;margin-bottom:12px;padding:8px;border:5.5px groove white; text-align:center;">
'''Hurricane Typhoid''' was the first documented severe '''Weather Event''', occurring during an exploration mission after '''Level 369''' was initially discovered. During the broadcast, '''Hurricane Typhoid''' was classified as a "Category 7 Blood Typhoon". During the storm, it rained a torrential downpour of regular water with a mix of medical syringes, rubbing alcohol, and human blood that quickly flooded the level's streets. Most of the exploration team perished due to being unaware of the buildings' indestructible properties, with only one operative surviving.
</span>
</div>

|-|Summer Storm Daniella (1996)=
<span style="color:black; text-shadow: 0 0 4px white, 0 0 6px white, 0 0 8px white, 0 0 10px white"></span>
<div style="background-color:bisque;color:black;margin:auto;margin-bottom:12px;padding:8px;border:5.5px groove navajowhite; text-align:center;">
'''Summer Storm Daniella''' was '''Level 369's''' second documented severe '''Weather Event''', occurring once the level began to become inhabited by various colonies and groups. The broadcast preceding the storm denounced it as a "Major Heatstorm". A mixture of sand, sea salt, and glass shards blew across '''Level 369''' as the temperature sharply rose to 123 degrees Fahrenheit (50.5 degrees Celsius). Residents took precautions and located shelter, though ten casualties were reported.
</span>
</div>

|-|Super Typhoon Jasper (2000)=
<span style="color:black; text-shadow: 0 0 4px white, 0 0 6px white, 0 0 8px white, 0 0 10px white"></span>
<div style="background-color:turquoise;color:black;margin:auto;margin-bottom:12px;padding:8px;border:5.5px groove turquoise; text-align:center;">
'''Super Typhoon Jasper''' was the third documented severe '''Weather Event''' on '''Level 369''', occurring when the level experienced a large increase in residents. The storm was designated as a "20.0 on the Richards Scale" and having the potential of "bringing tsunamis from the immediate coastline". Large amounts of water began to fall and collect on the ground, initially starting small before increasing to a large flood. After two hours, a five-mile-tall wave washed over '''Level 369''', burying the entire level underwater. Due to residents taking adequate procedures and having prior knowledge of '''Level 369's''' unpredictable weather, no casualties were reported.
</span>
</div>
</tabber>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="6">《 Colonies and Outposts 》</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
Despite '''Level 369's''' unpredictable weather, the level is a hotspot for various colonies due to its plentiful resources and suitability for long-term habitation. The most prominent settlements are listed below:
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="5">《 Town of Hartsfield 》</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
'''The Town of Hartsfield''' is a group occupying the town northeast of '''The Station''', named after the group's "mayor", Sherri Hartsfield. '''Hartsfield''' has a population of 1000 residents and is known for offering a wide range of recreational activities as a result of a sports complex that was established there. '''Hartsfield''' functions as the main outpost of '''Level 369''' and is open to trade.
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="5">《 Lakeside Heights 》</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
'''Lakeside Heights''' occupies a small section of '''Level 369's''' suburbia, located 2 miles northeast of '''Hartsfield'''. Residents can often be spotted doing traditional suburbanite activities, such as barbeques, outdoor walks, and swimming in a large lake located in the center. The lake functions as the most well-renowned portion of '''Lakeside Heights''' and has been declared safe to drink. '''Lakeside Heights''' has a population of 500. Similarly to '''Hartsfield''', they are also friendly and open to trade.
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="5">《 Rancher's Association 》</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
'''The Rancher's Association''' is the primary colony within the rural outer regions, located 60 miles away from the '''Station''' in the southeast direction. The settlement is populated with individuals who enjoy a more relaxed farm lifestyle. The settlement is currently trying to improvise a way to grow crops in the level's soil, though a lack of fertilizer and nearby water prevents crops from sprouting. '''The Rancher's Association''' currently has a population of 20. Unlike other outposts, the '''Rancher's Association''' is more hostile to outsiders and rarely accepts new residents.
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="5">《 [[Backroom Colonists]] Weather Watch Outpost 》</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
'''The Weather Watch Outpost''' is a base operated by the [[Backroom Colonists]], located in a large building to the southwest of '''The Station'''. Population of the base ranges from 45 to 60 as people are continually transferred in a moving cycle. '''The Weather Watch Outpost''' often interacts with '''The Town of Hartsfield''' and is open to trade.
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="5">《 <s>Anti Weatherman Coalition</s> 》</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
'''The Anti Weatherman Coalition''' was a group occupying a set of buildings in the northwest of the '''Station'''. The group believed that the '''Weatherman''' was evil and utilizing '''Level 369''' for malicious intentions, and that if they managed to kill the '''Weatherman''', all '''Weather Events''' would cease. The group attempted raids of the '''Station''' to locate the '''Weatherman''', which ultimately resulted in many being forced out of '''Level 369''' or dying completely. The group also attempted to "domesticate" the '''News Crew''' to join their cause, only amplifying their losses. Eventually, the outpost disbanded. At its peak, the '''Anti Weatherman Coalition''' amassed over 120 individuals.
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="6">《 Entrances and Exits 》</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="5">《 Entrances 》</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
*Turning on a TV within [[Level 3]], [[Level 9]], [[Level 27]] or [[Level 231]] will reveal the most recent broadcast. If one watches the entirety of it, any exits will bring one to '''Level 369''' instead.

*Finding a corridor that leads above ground in [[Level 148]] will lead one to '''Level 369'''.

*Regions within [[Level 211]] may transition into '''Level 369'''.

*Entering a house with the address 369 on [[Level 318]] leads to '''Level 369'''.

*Entering a blue "EMPLOYESS ONLY" door on [[Level 359]] will bring one to '''Level 369'''.

*Random noclipping within [[Level 365]] has a 5% chance to send one to '''Level 369'''.
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="5">《 Exits 》</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
*Getting "forced out" of '''Level 369''' will cause one to wake up within [[Level 370]], with any future attempts at reentry sending one there instead.

*Specific '''Weather Events''' relating to heat will sweep one away to [[Level 46]] though this is not recommended due to the risks involved.

*Diving to the bottom of a lake whilst holding a piece of trash will cause the water around to become cold. Swimming up from this point causes one to resurface on [[Level 375]]. Exploiting this exit may also send one to various levels depending on the object withheld. Clutching a neon light sends one to [[Level 399]], a piece of wood [[Level 416]], and an artifact that one may deem "familiar" or "nostalgic" transports them to [[Level 434]].

*Entering a movie theater in the northwest corner of the ring road sends one to either [[Level 444]] or [[Spectacle]].

*Noclipping into a computer within '''The Station''' sends one to [[Level 595]].

*Entering a slide that disappears beneath the ground will send one to either [[Level 694]] or [[Level 818]].

*A dark hallway in '''The Station''' leads to [[Level 959|somewhere you don't want to know]].

